The RSS feeds from monitoring all changes creates a lot of entries - especially minor changes (such as spelling correction).

To keep the list concise, and to the point, it'd be nice to be able to optionally filter out and modifications that were marked as 'Minor', or as in Confluence 4, those marked without 'Notify Watchers'.

It's impossible to insert text in front of a link that's part of a list in the new editor in Confluence 4. So, for example, where I used to have wiki text:

{noformat}
# [TICKET-123|http://link/to/ticket]: Ticket Name
{noformat}

in the new editor, I position the cursor at the start of the text, and type:

{noformat}
(!)
{noformat}

and the (!) symbol appears. However, I then press "space", with the intention of ending up with the equivalent of what would have been:

{noformat}
# (!) [TICKET-123|http://link/to/ticket]: Ticket Name
{noformat}

but instead, the cursor jumps to the end of the text, and I get:

{noformat}
# [(!)TICKET-123|http://link/to/ticket] : Ticket Name
{noformat}

What used to take a second to edit, now takes a minute.

A user will fail to login if the *total* number of failed login attempt is too large. Resetting the [current failed login count|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONF35/Resetting+the+Login+Count+for+a+User] in {{Confluence Admin >> Manage Users}} will not resolve the issue either. This affects all pre-4.0 Confluence versions.

h3.Workaround
Reset the total failed login count by running this query in the database:
{code}
UPDATE os_propertyentry SET INT_VAL = 0 WHERE entity_key = 'user.login.total_number_failed_login_attempts' AND entity_name = 'CWD_<username>';
{code}
Replace <username> with the affected user's username.

Note that this is resolved in Confluence 4.0 and above, which uses the logininfo table, instead of os_propertyentry to record failed login attempts.

h4.Description
Upgrade OOB 3513 with 1 page with in-page anchor.

Upgraded instance shows the same page with anchor as #anchorname.

h4. Workaround
You can inject SQL query to remove the hash from the link. For example this is the SQL query for MySQL.
{code}
UPDATE BODYCONTENT SET BODY = REPLACE(BODY, 'link-body>#', 'link-body>') WHERE BODY LIKE '%ac:anchor%link-body>#%';
{code}

I have a custom macro which renders the following markup into the page:

{code}
#requireResource("custom.macro.suite:multimediaplayer-resources")
#set ($baseUrl = $settingsManager.getGlobalSettings().getBaseUrl())
#set ($playerUrl = $baseUrl+$webResourceManager.getStaticPluginResource("custom.macro.suite:multimediaplayer-resources","player.swf"))
#set ($skinUrl = $baseUrl+$webResourceManager.getStaticPluginResource("custom.macro.suite:multimediaplayer-resources","blueratio.zip"))
#set ($fileUrl = $baseUrl+$downloadPathWithoutVersion)
#set ($rnd = "id_"+$hashCode)

<div id="$rnd">$action.getText("custom.macro.suite.multimediaplayer.loading.msg")</div>
<script type="text/javascript">
/* <![CDATA[ */
    jwplayer("$rnd").setup({
        flashplayer: "$playerUrl",
        file: "$fileUrl",
		height: $height,
		width: $width,
		skin: "$skinUrl",
		autostart: "$autostart"
    });
/* ]]> */
</script>
{code}

if I put the {toc}-macro in the same page it doesn't render but is displaying the following error:

{noformat}
Error rendering macro 'toc' : [com.ctc.wstx.exc.WstxLazyException] com.ctc.wstx.exc.WstxParsingException: String ']]>' not allowed in textual content, except as the end marker of CDATA section at [row,col {unknown-source}]: [171,5]
{noformat}

As far as I know, the cdata-section in my markup is perfectly valid and shouldn't have any effect on the {toc}-macro.

